decomposition = STL(canada_data["Vehicle Sales"], period=12).fit()  # using period=12 for monthly data

fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=1, figsize=(12, 8), sharex=True)
ax1.plot(decomposition.observed)
ax1.set_ylabel('Observed')

ax2.plot(decomposition.trend)
ax2.set_ylabel('Trend')

ax3.plot(decomposition.seasonal)
ax3.set_ylabel('Seasonal')

ax4.plot(decomposition.resid)
ax4.set_ylabel('Residuals')

fig.autofmt_xdate()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [5]:
# Function to perform the Dickey-Fuller test
def adfuller_test(series):
    result = adfuller(series)
    print("ADF Statistic:", result[0])
    print("P-Value:", result[1])

# Applying the Dickey-Fuller test on the vehicle sales data
adfuller_test(canada_data["Vehicle Sales"])

ADF Statistic: -1.5568336208081281
P-Value: 0.5052329640212231

from pmdarima import auto_arima
auto_model = auto_arima(train_data['Vehicle Sales'],  
                        seasonal=True,  
                        m=12,
                        d=1,
                        trace=True,  # print fit status on the screen
                        error_action='warn', 
                        suppress_warnings=True,  # suppress warnings
                        stepwise=True)  # stepwise algorithm intelligently selects the best model

# Print the summary of the best ARIMA model found
print(auto_model.summary())

# Make predictions
forecast, conf_int = auto_model.predict(n_periods=12, return_conf_int=True)

# Optionally, plot the actuals vs forecast for visualization

# Calculate MAPE
def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred): 
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(test_data['Vehicle Sales'], forecast)
print(f"MAPE: {mape:.2f}%")

MAPE: 8.08%

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error

# Forecasted values (log-transformed and then exponentiated to original scale)
forecasted_values = np.exp(forecast_log)

# Actual values
actual_values = test_data['Vehicle Sales']

# Calculate MAE
mae = mean_absolute_error(actual_values, forecasted_values[:12])
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.2f}")

# Calculate RMSE
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual_values, forecasted_values[:12]))
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): {rmse:.2f}")

# Calculate MAPE
mape = np.mean(np.abs((actual_values - forecasted_values) / actual_values[:12])) * 100
print(f"Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): {mape:.2f}%")

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Load the dataset
canada_data = pd.read_excel('/Users/zhangliuting/Downloads/Dissertation/(1)Canada.xlsx', parse_dates=['Month'])
canada_data.set_index('Month', inplace=True)
vehicle_sales = canada_data['Vehicle Sales']

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
import pmdarima as pm

# Load the dataset
canada_data = pd.read_excel('/Users/zhangliuting/Downloads/Dissertation/(1)Canada.xlsx', parse_dates=['Month'])
canada_data.set_index('Month', inplace=True)
vehicle_sales = canada_data['Vehicle Sales']

# Manually difference the data
diff_data = vehicle_sales.diff().dropna()  # First difference

# Split data into training and test sets (e.g., last 12 months as test data)
train_data = diff_data[:-12]
test_data = vehicle_sales[-12:]  # No need to difference test data here

# Check stationarity of differenced data
adf_result = adfuller(train_data)
print('ADF Statistic after differencing:', adf_result[0])
print('p-value after differencing:', adf_result[1])

# Decompose the differenced time series data
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(train_data, model='additive', period=12)  # adjust period accordingly

# Plot the decomposed components
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
decomposed = decomposition.plot()
plt.show()

# Automatically fit a seasonal ARIMA model to the differenced data
best_model = pm.auto_arima(train_data,
                           seasonal=True,
                           m=12,
                           start_p=0, start_q=0, start_P=0, start_Q=0,
                           max_p=3, max_q=3, max_P=2, max_Q=2,
                           trace=True,
                           stepwise=True,
                           error_action='ignore',
                           suppress_warnings=True)

print(best_model.summary())

# Predict the next 12 months
forecast, conf_int = best_model.predict(n_periods=12, return_conf_int=True)

# Calculate the last value in the original training dataset
last_value = vehicle_sales.iloc[-13]

# Reintegrate the predictions
reintegrated_forecast = np.cumsum(np.r_[last_value, forecast].astype(float))[-12:]

# Compare forecast against actual sales
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(vehicle_sales.index[-12:], test_data, label='Actual Sales', marker='o')
plt.plot(vehicle_sales.index[-12:], reintegrated_forecast, label='Forecasted Sales', marker='o')

plt.title('Vehicle Sales Forecast vs Actual')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Vehicle Sales')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Calculate and print the mean squared error
mse = mean_squared_error(test_data, reintegrated_forecast)
print('Mean Squared Error:', mse)

import statsmodels.api as sm

fitted_full_model = SARIMAX(vehicle_sales,
                            order=(1, 0, 1),
                            seasonal_order=(1, 0, 0, 12)).fit(disp=False)

residuals = fitted_full_model.resid

# Plotting residuals
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.plot(residuals)
plt.title('Residuals from SARIMAX Model')
plt.show()

# Density plot of residuals
residuals.plot(kind='kde')
plt.title('Density Plot of Residuals')
plt.show()

# Statistical test for normality (Jarque-Bera Test)
jb_test = sm.stats.jarque_bera(residuals)
print(f"Jarque-Bera statistic: {jb_test[0]}, p-value: {jb_test[1]}")

# Ljung-Box test for no autocorrelation
lb_test = sm.stats.acorr_ljungbox(residuals, lags=[10], return_df=True)
print(lb_test)
